PROJECT ARCHITECTURE EXPLANATION (FOR HUMANS)

WHY THIS STRUCTURE EXISTS

Earlier in development it was unclear where different types of logic should live.
That caused backend logic to be placed in routes, frontend logic to grow too large, and responsibilities to mix.

To fix this, we now follow a strict layered structure.

The goal is:
Clear separation of concerns
Predictable file placement
Reusable UI components
Small, readable routes
Features that are self-contained
Backend logic that is not tied to Flask

This structure is designed to be simple enough for everyone to understand, while still scalable.


THE FOUR LAYERS

The application is divided into four conceptual layers:
Components (Reusable UI pieces)
Features (Vertical functionality)
Pages (Screen composition)
Services (Backend feature logic)

Think of it like this:
Component → Feature → Page
and
Route → Service → DB


COMPONENTS (Frontend Building Blocks)

Location:
static/js/components/
static/css/components/

A component is a small reusable UI element.

Examples:
Search bar
Photo upload input
Tag selector
Modal
Reusable button

A component:
Manages only its own UI state
Receives data and callbacks
Does not call the backend directly
Does not contain business logic
If you can reuse it in another feature, it’s a component.
If it contains business logic, it is not a component.


FEATURES (Vertical Functionality)

Location:
static/js/features/
static/css/features/

A feature represents one complete piece of user behaviour.

Examples:

Upload Post
Discover Search
Follow Barber
Like Post

A feature:
Imports and composes components
Handles interaction logic
Calls backend routes via fetch()
Manages feature-level state
A feature should be self-contained.
If you removed the feature file, that functionality should disappear cleanly.
Features are not reusable UI pieces — components are.


PAGES (Screen Composition)

Location:
static/js/pages/
static/css/pages/

A page:
Initializes features
Connects DOM elements
Contains minimal logic

Pages should not:
Contain business logic
Perform validation
Call the database directly
Duplicate feature logic
A page simply wires things together.


SERVICES (Backend Logic)

Location:
app/services/

Each feature that requires backend logic gets one service file.

Example:
services/upload_post_service.py

A service:
Validates input
Handles file system operations
Calls database query functions
Returns structured results

A service must NOT:
Contain route decorators
Render templates
Return HTML
Contain frontend code
Services are pure backend feature logic.


ROUTES (app.py)

Routes must remain thin.

A route should:
Receive the request
Call the service
Render a template or return JSON

A route should NOT:
Contain complex validation
Contain file system logic
Contain database queries
If a route becomes long, the logic belongs in a service.


DATABASE LAYER

Location:
app/db/

This folder contains:

Database connection logic
Raw query functions

No business logic.
No Flask rendering.
No validation.

Only database interaction.


HOW TO ADD A NEW FEATURE

Example: Adding a "Create Comment" feature.

Create frontend feature file:
static/js/features/createComment.js

Create optional feature CSS:
static/css/features/createComment.css

Create backend service:
services/create_comment_service.py

Add thin route in app.py:
route calls the service only

Page initialises the feature


HOW TO DECIDE WHERE CODE BELONGS

Ask yourself:
Is this reusable UI?
→ Component
Is this user behaviour that may call backend?
→ Feature
Is this backend validation or filesystem logic?
→ Service
Is this SQL?
→ db/queries.py
Is this wiring features to a screen?
→ Page

If you’re unsure, ask before placing the code.


WHY THIS MATTERS

Without structure:
Files grow too large
Responsibilities mix
Code becomes hard to debug
Features become difficult to reuse
Onboarding becomes confusing

With this structure:
Every file has a clear purpose
New contributors know where to add code
AI tools generate correct structure
Features scale cleanly


FINAL PRINCIPLE

Keep things simple.
If a file starts doing too many different jobs, it is in the wrong place.


----- How to run locally via VSC terminal -----

Create/activate the virtual environment (Windows PowerShell):
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate

Install dependencies:
pip install -r requirements.txt

Run Flask:
python -m app.app
Then Ctrl+click the http://127.0.0.1:5000/ link


----- Database notes (safe defaults) -----

Database credentials should not be hard-coded in Python files.
Use a .env file or environment variables (and keep .env in .gitignore).
All SQL and DB access should go through app/db/ rather than being written inside routes.


----- Rules of thumb ----- 

No SQL in route functions → put it in app/db/
No business logic in templates → keep templates focused on presentation
No API keys or any sensitive info stored in Git → use environment variables / .env (ignored)
Keep pages small → use base.html and blocks to avoid duplication